      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the mystery of the disappearing principal balance! It's like watching a sneaky goblin in the shadows, isn't it? When you make your monthly payments, a part of that money goes towards the interest, which is the goblin's fee for borrowing your money. The rest goes towards reducing the principal balance, which is like trying to catch that elusive goblin in the dark. The interest is calculated based on the remaining principal balance, so the more you owe, the more goblin fees you pay. It's like the goblin gets richer the more you owe, and the less you see in your pocket. But don't worry, every payment you make is like throwing a net to catch the goblin, slowly reducing the amount you owe. Keep at it, and you'll eventually catch that goblin and make it pay up!",
