    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait i dont get the goblin thing lol. can u just explain the math part? like what is the actual formula they use to figure out the interest for the month? is it based on the total balance or something else?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the goblin confusion! Let's dive into the math without the mythical creatures. The interest on a student loan is typically calculated using the following formula:\n\nInterest for the month = Principal Balance x Monthly Interest Rate\n\nThe monthly interest rate is determined by dividing the annual interest rate by 12 (since there are 12 months in a year). So, if you have a student loan with an annual interest rate of 5%, the monthly interest rate would be approximately 0.00417 (5% divided by 12).\n\nFor example, if your remaining principal balance is $10,000, the interest for the month would be:\n\nInterest for the month = $10,000 x 0.00417 = $41.70\n\nSo, out of your monthly payment, $41.70 would go towards interest, and the rest would go towards reducing the principal balance. The more you owe, the more interest you pay, which is why it might feel like a lot of your money is going towards interest rather than reducing the principal. Over time, as you continue to make payments, the principal balance decreases, and so does the interest you pay each month.",
